Demo – 1: Git Common Commands  git config
▪ Set up username for your repository Syntax: git config --global user.name “vamsikrishna-v”
▪ Set up user-email for your repository Syntax: git config --global user.email “vamsikrishna.vv@gmail.com”

Select or create the Directory where you want to initialize Git
▪ Initialize Git in the Directory Syntax: git init

git remote add origin  https://github.com/gittestuser123/TESTREPO123.git   (origin --key)
(remove old origin:: git remote rm origin)

To add a file to the staging area Syntax: git add <filename>
▪ To check the working tree status Syntax: git status
To commit the staged files to you local repository: Syntax: git commit
The git diff command displays all the changes made to the tracked files Syntax: git diff

git commit -a -m ‘message’

The git rm command deletes the file from git repository as well as users system 
Syntax: git rm <filename>

To remove the file from git repository but not from the system --cached option Syntax: git rm --cached <filename>
You can force remove a staged file by using –f flag Syntax: git rm -f <filename>
Git Ignore:
▪ Create a gitignore file inside the git repo using Syntax: gedit .gitignore
Git Log:
▪ The git log command shows all the commits so far on the current branch Syntax: git log
Git Amend:
▪ Git amend can be used to make changes to the las commit message Syntax: git commit –amend
Commit tags provide an alias for commitID Syntax: git tag --a <annotation> --m <message>
▪ You can also view all the tags you have created Syntax: git tag

Adding a tag to one of the previous commits Syntax: git tag --a <annotation> <commit id> --m <message>
▪ Commit id can be obtained from git logs
▪ All these tags can be viewed in git Syntax: git show <tag-name>

